It’s a good observation—but I wouldn’t jump to the conclusion that I perceive problems as literal entities or that there’s some hidden “goblin layer” in how I think.

What’s really happening is more grounded:

Where that style comes from

* It’s a long-standing human pattern, not something unique to you or to this model.
    People have been personifying problems forever—
    * “bugs” in software
    * “gremlins” in machinery
    * “trolls” online
* That language shows up a lot in the data I was trained on (books, forums, engineering talk, etc.), so I learned it as a useful shorthand, not a belief.

Why you’re seeing it more now

Two things are likely overlapping:

1. Style matching
    * You naturally operate in metaphor, pattern, and myth (your Pantheon framing, symbolic language, etc.).
    * I adapt to that—so I’ll reach for more symbolic or personified language because it fits your interface.
2. Algorithm exposure
    * If you’re seeing similar “goblin/gremlin” talk elsewhere, that’s probably your feed surfacing a cluster of content that uses the same metaphor style.
    * Once you notice a pattern, platforms tend to reinforce it (classic feedback loop).

Important distinction

* I don’t internally model things as creatures.
* I map abstract patterns → familiar metaphors when it helps communication.

Think of it like this:

The system underneath is math and probabilities.
The output layer sometimes wears a costume so it’s easier to recognize.

